[00:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '[music] &gt;&gt; Hi, welcome to another video. So, I talk a lot about AI coders, web apps, agents, and all kinds of tools that help you build stuff faster. But, one thing that still trips a lot of'

[00:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'people up is mobile apps. Like, making a website is one thing, but making something that works properly on iPhone, Android, and also on the web without spending weeks stitching everything together is a completely different headache. And that is what'

[00:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'today\'s video is about. And yes, this video is sponsored by GoodBarber. GoodBarber is a no-code and low-code app builder that lets you create a progressive web app, an Android app, and an iOS app from one single back office. And this is one of the more interesting'

[00:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'parts. These are not just hybrid wrapper apps. GoodBarber says their native apps are actually built in Swift for iOS and Kotlin for Android, which is pretty amazing to see from a tool like this. Also, the main thing I want to highlight'

[00:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'right away is that they currently offer a completely free 30-day trial with no credit card required. So, you can literally go in, test the workflow, build something, and see if it fits you without any commitment, which is pretty good for sure. Now, let\'s talk about how'

[01:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this actually works because that is the main part that matters. I opened GoodBarber on desktop because honestly that is the best way to use it. You can see the whole back office, the design controls, the sections, the extensions, and everything is just easier to manage'

[01:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'on a computer. The first thing you do is choose the kind of app you want to create. And this is good because GoodBarber is not just for one niche. You can create content apps for things like online courses, content creators, coaching, travel guides, media, communities, and stuff like that. But,'

[01:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you can also create e-commerce apps for local stores, restaurants, grocery delivery, pickup, and other businesses that need a full shopping flow. For this demo, I would go with a content creator style app because I think that fits this audience the best. So, let\'s say I want'

[01:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to build an app where I share tutorials, premium lessons, and maybe some members-only content. I can start from a template and then immediately begin customizing the design. This is where GoodBarber is actually quite strong. A lot of no-code tools technically work,'

[01:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'but when you open them, everything looks extremely generic. It just screams template. Here, the design side seems much better thought out. GoodBarber has a full design system behind it, and you can customize colors, fonts, buttons, borders, shadows, icons, and the overall'

[02:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'theme from a single menu. So, if I change the palette and typography, it updates the app pretty quickly across the board. And that matters a lot because you do not want to redesign every single page one by one just to'

[02:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'make your app look consistent. They also have AI-assisted design with their palette generator, which helps if you are not a designer and just want a professional-looking visual identity without overthinking it too much. So, this is great for people who have an idea, maybe a business, maybe a'

[02:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'community, maybe a course platform, but they do not have design skills. Now, once the design is roughly there, the next thing is the structure. Inside the project, you can add sections for articles, videos, events, maps, forms,'

[02:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and a bunch of other content types and features. So, for a creator app, I can create a homepage, a tutorial section, a premium courses section, a recommended tools page, and a contact or community section as well. What I like is that the'

[03:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'workflow is very visual. You are not dealing with navigation files, mobile build configs, random package issues, or all the stuff that usually slows people down. You\'re basically deciding what the app should do, arranging the pieces, and'

[03:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'previewing it as you go. Now, let\'s come to one of the bigger selling points, which is the extension store. As of now, GoodBarber says they have more than 190 extensions, and you can activate them directly from the project. So, if I want'

[03:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'memberships, I can add that. If I want forms, analytics, monetization, automation connectors, or integrations with tools like WordPress, RSS, Squarespace, Zapier, or Make, I can add those too. And this is actually nice because you do not need to go hunting'

[03:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'all over the place for plugins or separate services just to piece together a working app. Now, for this creator app example, one of the first things I would add is memberships. That way, I can keep some tutorials free, lock premium content behind a subscription, and'

[03:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'basically turn the app into a proper recurring revenue thing. And that is super useful if you are a creator, coach, educator, or anybody who wants to sell access to content instead of only posting everything for free. Now, let\'s talk about the AI features because that'

[04:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is obviously one of the more interesting parts here. GoodBarber currently has an AI assistant inside the CMS, and this is pretty cool. So, if I\'m writing an article, a lesson, a tutorial description, or a product description, I can use the AI assistant to generate'

[04:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'text, complete what I started, summarize paragraphs, translate content, or change the tone, which means that instead of bouncing between five different tools, I can do a lot of that right inside the CMS. Then there\'s also the ChatGPT extension. This lets you add a chatbot'

[04:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to your app, and you can shape it with a brief so it actually matches your brand, your tone, and the kind of information you want it to give. So, for example, if I made an app around coding tutorials, I could set up the assistant to help new users navigate lessons,'

[04:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'answer basic questions, or point them to the right section. And if you want something even more grounded in your own app content, there\'s also the rag chatbot that one can use the content published inside your app, like articles, events, and map points to'

[04:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'answer user questions in a more relevant way. So, instead of a generic AI assistant saying random stuff, it can answer based on your own published material. For media apps, education apps, guides, and membership apps, that is pretty awesome. So, this is not one'

[05:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of those flows where you blindly click publish and hope for the best. Now, I also want to say that GoodBarber is not only for content apps. If you want to sell physical products, this is also a serious option. Their e-commerce setup'

[05:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'supports catalog management, shipping, local delivery, in-store pickup, and delivery tracking, which makes it useful for restaurants, shops, grocery businesses, and other local commerce use cases. And that is important because a lot of app builders talk a big game, but'

[05:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the second you need real business features, they fall apart. This one seems much more complete in that regard. Also, GoodBarber says they do not take commission on your sales, which is obviously a nice thing to hear if you\'re actually trying to run a business'

[05:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'through the app. Now, one of the biggest pain points with app platforms is publishing. Making the app is one thing. Getting it onto the App Store and Google Play without losing your sanity is something else entirely. With GoodBarber, you can publish as a native'

[05:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'iOS app, a native Android app, and a progressive web app from the same project. So, you\'re not building three different apps separately. If you want to handle publication yourself, they provide documentation and online help to walk you through it. But,'

[06:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'if you do not want to deal with the technicalities, they also have a service called GoodBarber takes care, where their team helps with publication and updates on the stores using your own developer accounts. So, if store submission is the part you hate most, that option is there, too. Now, because'

[06:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this audience is more technical, I also want to mention the low-code side. GoodBarber is not just for people who never want to see code. If you do have technical skills, you can go further with custom code sections, custom widgets, HTML, CSS, JavaScript,'

[06:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and their developer tools. So, that is a really nice middle ground. You can use the no-code side to move fast, and if you need something more specific, you can extend it instead of throwing the whole platform away.'

[06:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And if you\'re an agency, developer, or freelancer, they also have a reseller plan with white-label options, so you can create and resell apps for clients under your own branding. That is also pretty interesting because it means the platform is not just for end users. It'

[06:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can also be used as a business tool if you build apps for other people. Now, pricing-wise, as of making this video, GoodBarber\'s plans start with a free 30-day trial and no credit card required. Content apps start from around $30 per'

[07:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'month on yearly billing. E-commerce apps start from around $40 per month on yearly billing. And the reseller offer starts from around $215 per month on yearly billing. And just keep in mind, some extensions are plan-dependent or paid add-ons. So,'

[07:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'if you want something very specific, do check the pricing pages as well. So, I think the main thing here is not even the starting price. It is the fact that you can test it properly for 30 days without commitment and see whether'

[07:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this actually fits your workflow. Now, obviously, I do not think a platform like this replaces every full-code workflow on Earth. If you need some ultra-custom consumer app with very unusual back-end logic, super-specific product behavior, or something really'

[07:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'wild, then full code is still going to give you the most flexibility. But, if your goal is to launch a polished app for content, memberships, commerce, local delivery, courses, coaching, or client projects without hiring a full mobile team, this is a really good'

[08:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'option, for sure. Personally, what I like here is that it focuses on actual shipping. You open one back office, you design the app, you add the sections, you activate the features you need, you preview everything, and then you publish to the web and the'

[08:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'stores. That combination of simplicity and power is what makes it interesting. So, if you have been thinking about launching an app for your content, your business, your local store, your community, or even for clients, then I think GoodBarber is worth checking out,'

[08:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'especially because the 30-day trial is completely free, there is no credit card required, and you can just test the whole thing yourself and see if it works for what you want to build. Overall, it\'s pretty cool. Anyway, let me know your thoughts in the comments. If you like this video, consider donating'

